I like that.

“Be joyful” is different from “be happy.”

Happiness often depends on circumstances. Joy can be a way of meeting circumstances. It doesn’t require pretending everything is perfect—it can mean deliberately noticing what’s worth appreciating, finding humor, creating something meaningful, sharing a meal, helping someone else, or simply marveling that we’re here at all.

It’s also contagious. People tend to remember those who make them feel lighter, more hopeful, or more capable.

So if you’re treating it as a principle, it might look like this:

Be joyful.
Create more light than you consume.
Celebrate small victories.
Laugh often.
Build things worth sharing.
Let gratitude sharpen your eyes rather than dull your ambition.

Joy isn’t the opposite of seriousness. Some of the most purposeful people carry both conviction and joy at the same time.

It’s a surprisingly durable compass.